📖 Theory
What is a Package?

A package is software bundled with all required files.

Examples

nginx
git
docker
vim
curl
What is a Repository?

A repository is an online collection of packages.

Ubuntu downloads software from repositories configured in:

/etc/apt/sources.list
🛠️ Task 1 – Update Package List
sudo apt update

Understand:

Downloads the latest package index.
Does not install updates.
🛠️ Task 2 – Upgrade Packages
sudo apt upgrade

Updates installed software to newer versions.

🛠️ Task 3 – Full Upgrade
sudo apt full-upgrade

Handles dependency changes when upgrading.

🛠️ Task 4 – Search Packages
apt search nginx

Search for:

apt search docker
apt search python3
🛠️ Task 5 – Package Information
apt show git

Look for:

Version
Dependencies
Description
🛠️ Task 6 – Install Software

Install Git if needed:

sudo apt install git

Install Curl:

sudo apt install curl

Install Tree:

sudo apt install tree

Verify:

git --version
curl --version
tree --version
🛠️ Task 7 – Remove Packages

Remove:

sudo apt remove tree

Completely remove:

sudo apt purge tree

Clean unused packages:

sudo apt autoremove
🛠️ Task 8 – Package Cache

Clean cache:

sudo apt clean

Remove old cache:

sudo apt autoclean
🛠️ Task 9 – Using dpkg

List installed packages:

dpkg -l

Check if Git is installed:

dpkg -l | grep git

Package details:

dpkg -s git
🛠️ Task 10 – Snap Packages

Check Snap:

snap list

Install example:

sudo snap install hello-world

Run:

hello-world

Remove:

sudo snap remove hello-world
